# .cursorrules
#
# Primordial Elemental Tic-Tac-Toe
# --------------------------------
# This file serves as the comprehensive specification for the Primordial Elemental Tic-Tac-Toe game,
# detailing the rules, technical architecture, technologies, and implementation guidelines. It is
# designed to be easily maintainable, versionable, and extensible. All code references, constants,
# and rule variations must be documented in this file or in the associated .md documents.
#
# Table of Contents
# 1. Introduction
# 2. Architecture & Technologies
# 3. Configuration File (gameConfig.ts)
# 4. Application Flow
# 5. Game Mechanics & Rules
#   5.1 Order of Effects
#   5.2 Lineups & Scoring
#   5.3 Exclusion Zone
#   5.4 Spread Effect
#   5.5 Bonuses
# 6. End of Game
# 7. Proposed Symbols
# 8. Scalability & Documentation
# 9. Versioning & Changelog

################################################################################
# 1. INTRODUCTION
################################################################################
# Primordial Elemental Tic-Tac-Toe is an upgraded version of Tic-Tac-Toe played on
# a 9×9 grid (default), where players compete to align their elemental symbols and
# accumulate points. Each alignment or bonus triggers additional effects, ensuring
# deep and dynamic gameplay.

################################################################################
# 2. ARCHITECTURE & TECHNOLOGIES
################################################################################
# - Framework: React (TypeScript)
# - Main Language: TypeScript (front-end logic, game mechanics)
# - Proposed project structure (recommendation):
#   ├── src
#   │   ├── components
#   │   │   ├── Board.tsx         # Main component rendering the board
#   │   │   ├── Cell.tsx          # Component for each cell
#   │   │   ├── Lobby.tsx         # Waiting/invitation page
#   │   │   ├── HomePage.tsx      # Fun and thematic home page
#   │   │   └── ...               # Other reusable components
#   │   ├── core
#   │   │   ├── gameLogic.ts      # Main game rules (placements, alignments, etc.)
#   │   │   ├── spreadEffect.ts   # Logic for the Spread effect
#   │   │   ├── scoring.ts        # Scoring and points management
#   │   │   └── ...
#   │   ├── config
#   │   │   └── gameConfig.ts     # Centralized configuration file (see §3)
#   │   └── utils
#   │       └── helpers.ts        # Utility/helper functions
#   ├── docs
#   │   ├── gameLogic.md          # Detailed documentation of game logic
#   │   ├── spreadEffect.md       # Detailed documentation of the Spread effect
#   │   └── ...
#   └── package.json
#
# - Each major module (e.g. gameLogic, spreadEffect) has its own .md documentation
#   in the “docs” folder, covering its purpose and main functions.
# - The code should include explanatory comments at the beginning (purpose, usage)
#   and within important functions.

################################################################################
# 3. CONFIGURATION FILE (gameConfig.ts)
################################################################################
# All parameters and constants required to configure and adjust gameplay are
# defined here. Whenever a new global constant is introduced, it must be placed
# in this file. Example fields:
#
#  - GRID_SIZE: number (default 9; can be changed to vary board size)
#  - MAX_SCORE: number (default 12; the threshold to trigger game-end checks)
#  - SCORE_DIFFERENCE_FOR_WIN: number (default 5; minimum gap to confirm victory)
#  - SYMBOLS: string[] (list of possible symbols; e.g. ["🔥","💧","💨","🌍"])
#  - MAX_DEFINITIVE_SYMBOLS: number (limit for definitive symbols per player)
#  - MAX_BOOSTED_SYMBOLS: number (limit for boosted symbols per player)
#  - POINTS_FOR_THREE: number (default 1; points for 3-in-a-row)
#  - POINTS_FOR_FOUR: number (default 2; points for 4-in-a-row)
#  - POINTS_FOR_FIVE: number (default 3; points for 5-in-a-row)
#  - SPREAD_LIMIT_PER_TURN: number (max successive Spread activations in one turn)
#  - BONUS_CREATION_PROBABILITIES: object/array (e.g. { point:0.50, removeOpponent:0.30, spread:0.15, boostedSymbol:0.05 })
#  - ZONE_EXCLUSION_DURATION: number (in turns; how long a 5-in-a-row zone is blocked)
#  - ...
#
# All default values must be documented in-gameConfig.ts. 
# The code reading these values should remain flexible to accommodate variants.

################################################################################
# 4. APPLICATION FLOW
################################################################################
# 4.1 Home Page
#   - The entry point: a themed landing screen introducing the game setting and
#     presenting two buttons: “1v1” and “1v1v1” (icons or symbols can replace the “1”).
#   - The user selects the desired mode to create/join a game.
#
# 4.2 Lobby/Waiting Page
#   - After clicking “1v1” or “1v1v1,” the player is taken to a lobby page.
#   - A unique invitation link is automatically copied to the user’s clipboard.
#   - Displays the connected players. The game starts as soon as all required players join.
#
# 4.3 Starting the Game
#   - Symbols are randomly assigned to each player, ensuring uniqueness.
#   - The board is initialized empty with GRID_SIZE (default 9×9).
#   - Score counters start at zero; relevant config parameters (MAX_SCORE, etc.) are loaded.
#
# 4.4 Game in Progress
#   - Players place their symbols in turn.
#   - The underlying logic checks for alignments or special effects after each placement.

################################################################################
# 5. GAME MECHANICS & RULES
################################################################################

# 5.1 ORDER OF EFFECTS (after a symbol is placed)
#   1. Detect lineups (3, 4, or 5 in a row) in rows, columns, or diagonals.
#   2. For each lineup:
#       a) Award points based on lineup length (see §5.2).
#       b) Remove the aligned symbols (except definitive ones).
#       c) Place bonuses and definitive/boosted symbols as needed.
#       d) If it’s a 5-symbol lineup, activate the exclusion zone on those squares.
#   3. Trigger the Spread effect if any (see §5.4), observing SPREAD_LIMIT_PER_TURN.
#   4. Check if new lineups form because of Spread placements or boosted interactions.
#   5. Repeat steps 2–4 until no new lineups appear.
#   6. Check for any player’s score ≥ MAX_SCORE. If so, compare their score to the others:
#       - If the score gap ≥ SCORE_DIFFERENCE_FOR_WIN, that player wins immediately.
#       - Otherwise, continue the game.
#   7. If no winner emerges, end the turn and move to the next player.

# 5.2 LINEUPS & SCORING
#   - 3 symbols in a row => POINTS_FOR_THREE (default 1 point)
#   - 4 symbols in a row => POINTS_FOR_FOUR (default 2 points)
#   - 5 symbols in a row => POINTS_FOR_FIVE (default 3 points)
#
#   5.2.1. Consequences of Lineups
#       - 3-in-a-row:
#           - Remove the 3 aligned symbols.
#           - 2 of those squares (randomly) get bonuses.
#           - The last square gets a definitive symbol of the scoring player.
#       - 4-in-a-row:
#           - Remove the 4 aligned symbols.
#           - 3 squares (randomly) get bonuses.
#           - 1 square gets a boosted definitive symbol.
#       - 5-in-a-row:
#           - Remove the 5 aligned symbols.
#           - 2 boosted definitive symbols appear on 2 of those squares (random).
#           - Trigger the Spread effect 2 times for the scoring player.
#           - Activate an exclusion zone on these 5 squares for ZONE_EXCLUSION_DURATION.

# 5.3 EXCLUSION ZONE
#   - The squares involved in a 5-in-a-row become blocked for ZONE_EXCLUSION_DURATION turns.
#   - Neither normal placements nor Spread-generated symbols can occupy these squares
#     during that period.

# 5.4 SPREAD EFFECT
#   - When triggered, a symbol (of the player who initiated the effect) is placed:
#       1) On a free square adjacent to any existing symbol of that player.
#       2) If no adjacent square is free, place it randomly on a free square outside the exclusion zone.
#   - Boosted Symbol Interaction:
#       - If a newly placed symbol is adjacent to a boosted definitive symbol of the same player,
#         it spawns an additional symbol on a random free square. This can chain further
#         alignments (re-check lineups).

# 5.5 BONUSES
#   - Placed on squares when certain lineups occur.
#   - A bonus is activated when a player places a symbol on that square.
#   - Potential bonus effects (with example probabilities):
#       1) +1 immediate point
#       2) Remove one opponent’s (non-definitive) symbol at random
#       3) Trigger an additional Spread
#       4) Create a boosted symbol (5% chance)
#   - If the square is occupied by a definitive or boosted symbol, the bonus is ignored.

################################################################################
# 6. END OF GAME
################################################################################
# - Whenever a player reaches or surpasses MAX_SCORE (default 12):
#   - Check the score gap with the next highest-scoring player.
#   - If the gap ≥ SCORE_DIFFERENCE_FOR_WIN (default 5), that player wins outright.
#   - Otherwise, the game continues until the gap is sufficient or another condition arises
#     (e.g., optional turn limit).

################################################################################
# 7. PROPOSED SYMBOLS
################################################################################
# - Default set:
#   - Player 1: 🔥 (Fire)
#   - Player 2: 💧 (Water)
#   - Player 3: 💨 (Air)
#   - Player 4 (optional variant): 🌍 (Earth)
# - Each player receives a unique symbol randomly when the match begins.

################################################################################
# 8. SCALABILITY & DOCUMENTATION
################################################################################
# - Each module (Board, Cell, gameLogic, spreadEffect, etc.) has a dedicated .md file in /docs.
# - Provide a header comment in each file explaining its purpose and usage.
# - Significant functions, classes, or logic blocks require inline comments for clarity.
# - Any modifications to the rules or constants are mirrored in gameConfig.ts and documented
#   in the relevant .md file.

################################################################################
